---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Why Stainless Steel Wire Pegs Are Worth It"
  description="Discover why stainless steel wire pegs outlast plastic and wooden pegs, save you money, and are better for the environment. The complete guide."
>

  <section class="py-24 px-6 bg-navy-50">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-teal-500 mb-4">The Case For Wire Pegs</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-navy-900 leading-tight mb-6">Why Stainless Steel Wire Pegs Are Worth It</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-navy-600 leading-relaxed">Every broken plastic peg is a small piece of pollution that will outlast you by centuries. Australians throw away millions or simply lose them to the lawn mover! Wire pegs exist to end that cycle.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-16 px-6 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">

      <div class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-navy-900 mb-6">The problem with plastic pegs</h2>
        <p class="text-navy-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Plastic clothes pegs are one of those products that seem cheap until you realise how often you replace them. The spring rusts. The plastic deteriorates and then cracks in your fingers. They snap in half on a windy day, your clothes flying away.</p>
        <p class="text-navy-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The average Australian household buys a new pack of pegs every 1–2 years. Over a decade, that's 5–10 packs of pegs — most of which end up in landfill, because plastic pegs can't be recycled.</p>
        </div>

      <div class="mb-4">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-navy-900 mb-6">The problem with wooden pegs</h2>
        <p class="text-navy-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Wooden pegs feel like a sustainable alternative — but they have their own problems. Left outside, they absorb moisture, swell, crack, and eventually grow mould that transfers to your clean washing.</p>
        <p class="text-navy-600 leading-relaxed">The spring mechanism is still metal, still rusts, and still fails. Wooden pegs are better than plastic — but they're not the solution.</p>
      </div>
<div class="mb-4">
        <img src="/images/switch-plastic-for-steel.png" alt="Switch from plastic and wooden pegs to stainless steel wire pegs" class="w-full rounded-2xl mb-16" />
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-navy-900 mb-6">Why wire pegs are different</h2>
      <div class="mb-16">
        
        <p class="text-navy-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Wire Pegs are made from a single continuous piece of stainless steel wire — bent into shape. There is no spring. There is no separate clip. There are no parts to fail.</p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-8">
          <div class="bg-navy-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-navy-100">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-navy-900 mb-2">✓ Never breaks</h3>
            <p class="text-navy-600 text-sm">No spring mechanism nor weld points means nothing to snap or rust.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-navy-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-navy-100">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-navy-900 mb-2">✓ Won't stain clothes</h3>
            <p class="text-navy-600 text-sm">No rust transfer onto your clean white washing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-navy-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-navy-100">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-navy-900 mb-2">✓ Cools quickly</h3>
            <p class="text-navy-600 text-sm">Metal conducts heat away fast — safe to handle even on hot days.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-navy-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-navy-100">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-navy-900 mb-2">✓ Multi-purpose</h3>
            <p class="text-navy-600 text-sm">Use as food bag clips, paper clips, garden ties, and more.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>


      <div class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-navy-900 mb-6">Better for the environment</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Australians are pretty switched on about reducing waste. We bring our own bags, we compost, we think about reducing throwaway plastic. But pegs? They fly under the radar. Nobody's out here campaigning about clothes pegs.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">One set of wire pegs lasts decades. That's it — job done. Same line, same routine, just no more wasted petroleum or plastic casualties under the washing line.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-navy-900 text-white py-16 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold mb-4">Ready to make the switch?</h2>
      <p class="text-navy-100 mb-8">Not sure which grade is right for you? Use our Peg Finder first.</p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-center">
        <a href="/which-peg" class="bg-teal-500 text-white font-semibold px-8 py-4 rounded-full hover:bg-teal-700 transition-colors">Find My Peg →</a>
        <a href="https://www.biome.com.au/collections/wire-pegs" target="_blank" class="border border-navy-400 text-white font-semibold px-8 py-4 rounded-full hover:border-white transition-colors">Shop at Biome →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>